games of the elder scrolls series have some very clear expectations to them and must adhere to some very specific core concepts skyrim does not tarry too far from the mark this game has many weaknesses that almost universally stem from its multiplatform development  cities feel like villages and villages dont feel at all this is entirely because of the limitations of the engine and the consoles weapons and armour are one size fits all and all armours of the same material are identical there is no wear and tear of your items money from a thousand years ago does not draw comment when given to a vendor you have no useful journal system instead the map tells you exactly where to go for everything many things that disrupt the immersion within the game play this game once on a vanilla play through and then add in the mods the base game is good and it will help you appreciate the platform you are playing on a thousand times over when you play a second game using mods you will mod this title you will mod it to hell and back you will love it for the mods that shore up the weaknesses and enable new and wonderful things in the game steam workshop integration sounds nice but its not the games mod interface is garbage and the workshop prevents a lot of the mods you will want you will end up using nexus mods and their nexus mod manager or the slipstream mod manager to handle all your mods there are mods to patch problems to reenable content replace bad textures enhance combat add items add npcs whatever your heart may desire the mods are there the game is good genuinely good but it could have been so much better one hopes that fallout 4 learns the lessons presented by the mods of skyrim rather than dooming modders to recreating their efforts in the next version of the engine any gamer worth their salt has already got this game and has played at least some of it
