ive noticed that the reviews for morrowind oblivion and skyrim tend to be about why that game is the best elder scrolls game and the others are terrible in comparison i really enjoy all three of them sorry arena and daggerfall youre just not very enjoyable by todays standards so i figured ill give reviews for each that focus on whats unique about each of them and what kind of players that will appeal to skyrim is the most mainstream of the three its a big grand production meant for a big grand reception in other words this was the first tes game specifically designed to be in the headlines a ton think of it as the difference between a film with a 30 million dollar production budget and one with a 300 million production budget meant to be one of the grandest films of the decade morrowind and oblivion are the former skyrim is the latter its easily the most professional of the three as such the game is meant to be most appealing to a wide range of players morrowind is pure chaos oblivion is pure order and skyrim is somewhere between those two extremes its safe when it wants to be and wild when it wants to be it has some of the rugged freedom of morrowind while being polished like oblivion and therefore avoiding any of the major negatives that morrowind also has for the positives of the game lets go ahead and start with the graphics and scenery morrowind had rugged scenery but the graphics werent good enough to really be stunned by it oblivion had soft graphics and scenery which left you feeling perfectly content but not awed skyrim has both the graphics and scenery to take your breath away its rugged majestic powerful and all sorts of other things its easily the most immersive of any of the three games no matter how many thousands of hours youve spent playing it there will always be views that strike awe in you whenever a game can get you to willingly just stop and stand there and take in everything its succeeded skyrim does that all the time the skill and perk systems are also the best of any tes game it allows you to really forge your own path and adapt your character however you want as the game progresses morrowind and oblivion basically make you decide at the beginning exactly what type of character you want and keeps you confined to that choice skyrim is much more fluid and each playthrough is much more customizable which also allows you to add much more depth to the story you come up with for your character want to be a high elf who is disgusted by the actions of the aldmeri dominion and decides to shun magic and adopt the rugged combat and lifestyle of the local nords want to be an orc who feels no connection to the brute stregth emphasized in your culture and instead explore the arcane and master the ways of the mage want to be a redguard who shuns the sword and shield and instead masters the bow and slips silently through the shadows well in skyrim you can be any of those things and pretty much anything else you could possibly imagine another big positive is the crafting systems found in the game the smithing skill replaces the armorer skill and is a gigantic improvement you dont have to worry about maintaining your armor and weapons but instead you will be able to smith powerful weapons and armor the more time you devote to it if you want to have daedric weapons before you even hit level 20 you can but remember that it means you spent so much time smithing that your combat skills might not be up to par the same goes for brewing powerful potions or creating powerful enchantments its determined less by getting lucky and finding good stuff and more by deciding what to pursue for the negatives we have to go back to the earlier analogy about the hollywood films the 300 million dollar budget film has a ton of things that you could possibly want but it also cant take the risks or be as quirky as the 30 million dollar budget film so everything in skyrim is polished and streamlined and sometimes you find yourself wishing that it would be less powerful and more quirky or nuanced the magic is a good example there are fewer schools of magic and fewer varieties of spells no levitation no damage weapon or damage armor spells no school of mysticism etc destruction spells basically come in three varieties frost fire and shock there is a good variety of types of those spells cloak rune constant cast etc but sometimes you want to be able to hit someone with something other than frost fire or shock damage as a mage and in skyrim you cant the dlcs do add some good variety restoration school spells that do direct damge to undead or do posion damage conjuration spells that allow you to bring forth powerful creatures made of ash etc but its still less options than oblivion or morrowind gave you and thats really what a lot of the negatives of this game boil down to things you loved about oblivion and morrowind that werent included in skyrim it has so many improvements over those two but it also gets rid of some of the things people loved about them the soundtrack for example is a powerful soundtrack but it feels like its always in adrenalinepumping mode whereas morrowind and oblivion had music that would really draw you in emotionally its not that skyrims soundtrack is bad its just that morrowinds and oblivions were better overall overall this is the crown jewel of the tes series so far but that doesnt mean it was perfect youll love it and yet you will still sometimes prefer to play oblivion or morrowind instead
